The paper deals with computational complexity and algorithms for controlling the outcome of elections, which falls under the category of computational game theory (cs.GT). The use of algorithms and computational methods to manipulate the outcome of elections also suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The problem of adding a bundle of voters can be seen as a combinatorial optimization problem, which is a common topic in computer science and falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The study of voting rules and their properties is also related to machine learning and statistical inference, which are covered in the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
